{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532081"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:22:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:22:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14651"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14651"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.28,0.07,0.44,0.11,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7344"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57735"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7344"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14651"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43194"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"670"},{"type":"tags","id":"1731"},{"type":"tags","id":"3077"},{"type":"tags","id":"3230"},{"type":"tags","id":"4013"},{"type":"tags","id":"4050"},{"type":"tags","id":"4979"},{"type":"tags","id":"11639"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17932"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43551"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57735","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57735"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 81-year-old man is admitted to hospital with urosepsis. He has a medical history of Parkinson disease with dementia, hypertension, and osteoarthritis. His regular medications include levodopa-carbidopa, amitriptyline, amlodipine, and paracetamol. Following discussion with his family, a decision has been made to transition to comfort-focused care and he is awaiting transfer to the palliative care ward.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOver the past 24 hours, he has been intermittently refusing oral medications including his levodopa-carbidopa. On examination, he appears distressed. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 145/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. He has developed painful sustained muscle contractions of his neck causing torticollis, and his jaw is clenched. His consciousness is fluctuating.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management for his dystonia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transdermal rotigotine patch","Oral diazepam","Subcutaneous midazolam","Subcutaneous glycopyrrolate","Intramuscular haloperidol"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute dystonia due to missed doses of levodopa-carbidopa in the context of end-stage Parkinson disease. The inability to take oral medications necessitates an alternative route of administration for immediate symptom control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubcutaneous midazolam\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate choice as it provides rapid relief of muscle spasms through its action as a GABA receptor agonist. It can be easily administered despite the patient\u0027s clenched jaw, has quick onset of action, and can be continued as either regular doses or via continuous infusion if needed. It also has the benefit of reducing agitation and distress.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Etransdermal rotigotine patch\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered as part of a longer-term management plan to replace oral levodopa, but it would not provide the immediate relief needed for acute dystonia. Additionally, it can take 24-48 hours to achieve therapeutic levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral diazepam\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate given the patient\u0027s difficulty with oral intake due to his clenched jaw. Furthermore, oral medications generally have unreliable absorption in end-of-life care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubcutaneous glycopyrrolate\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used for managing excessive secretions in palliative care. While it has some antispasmodic properties, it would not be effective for acute dystonia of this severity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntramuscular haloperidol\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated as antipsychotic medications can worsen parkinsonian symptoms by blocking dopamine receptors, potentially exacerbating the dystonia. Additionally, intramuscular injection may be distressing for the patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter the acute episode is controlled, the medical team should implement a comprehensive plan for ongoing symptom management, including alternative routes for his regular medications to prevent recurrence of symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute dystonia can occur due to abrupt cessation of dopaminergic medications in Parkinson disease.","Subcutaneous midazolam is an effective treatment for acute dystonia in palliative care settings when oral medications cannot be administered.","Regular review of medication routes is essential in end-of-life care to ensure symptom control is maintained."],"references":["Lokk J, Delbari A. Clinical aspects of palliative care in advanced Parkinson\u2019s disease. BMC palliative care. 2012 Dec;11:1-8. Available online at ; https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/1472-684X-11-20#citeas","Raeder V, Boura I, Leta V, et al. Rotigotine Transdermal Patch for Motor and Non-motor Parkinson\u0027s Disease: A Review of 12 Years\u0027 Clinical Experience. CNS Drugs. 2021;35(2):215-231. doi:10.1007/s40263-020-00788-4. Available online at ; https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7871129/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43194"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14651"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43194","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43194"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-27T15:16:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-27T15:16:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7344"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57735"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"28","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/28"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc95","name":"Palliative Care","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"